A rare limited-edition timepiece from Grand Seiko, the true luxury watchmaker from Japan was unveiled for the first time in India by chess legend Viswanathan Anand. The event, aptly named “The Legends of Time” was followed by a one-on-one interaction over High Tea with members of the GS9 Club - Grand Seiko’s official group for owners of its luxury timepieces.
The timepiece unveiled at the event is encased in 18k rose gold and complete with diamonds. It is inspired by winters in Shinshu - home to Grand Seiko’s timepieces - where snow falls off branches, creating a shimmering cascade of light. The SBGY008G is powered by Grand Seiko’s iconic Spring Drive movement - one of the most precise in watchmaking. Only 60 timepieces of the SBGY008G are available worldwide.
SBGY008G - ₹33,00,000/- 
To discover more about this luxury timepiece, visit www.grandseikoboutique.in

latestPosts.caption:
Just the other day, an iconic room freshener brand was relaunched with a tagline that dates back three decades. Its idea of “puraani yaad” can easily get one a bit teary-eyed. It’s the 30-year-theory of the ‘nostalgia pendulum’ at work again – a socio-cultural phenomenon where trends repeat every three decades.
All through 2024, nostalgia ruled – Poppins and Phantom sweet cigarettes were back on the grocer’s shelves, boot-cut jeans, sneakers and bold graphic printed tees made a fashionable return on the streets. A web series based on the iconic Archie’s comic book series hit OTT platforms, along with a whole bunch of ’90s Hindi films running to packed theatres. Brand mavens believe the trend is here to stay, and have a cool name for it: ‘nostalgia marketing’. Selling memories to a world looking for a story with some solid roots, not just the reel-kind of 30 seconds.
It is what makes shows like Panchayat and films like 12th Fail garner critical acclaim, for a story arc, music, palette and tonality that ‘feels like a DD serial’.
It’s curious though. Nostalgia marketing works because things you aspired to as a child but couldn’t afford are all yours for the take – like that analogue camera, a Sony Walkman and uber-expensive Air Jordan sneakers.
And though most of Gen Z don’t remember the nineties, for example, research has found that 37% of them feel a strong connection to the decade. Thanks to residual memories of when their parents were happy, carefree teenagers, with zero stress. And life was tactile. A novel experience for the digital natives, who experience music, art, reading on screens.
It is the reason why Royal Enfield sells eight out of 10 bikes in the 350-500 cc engine category in India and the Fender Stratocaster guitar is in high demand worldwide. And despite 3D-printed dishes and AI in the kitchen, we are happy to pay top dollars for food experiences that recreate the past on a plate with recipes fished out from a grandmother’s diary.
Call it a rebound, but in an age of insta-gratification, young adults are hungry for now-stalgia. For all you know, it may just help bridge that thing called generational gap.
